ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-7 The number four connecting rod was found broken and colored blue. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-5 Number one, four, five, and six crankshaft journals revealed distress. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-3 The cylinders in the area of the 'B' nut were found with a dark, oily substance coating them. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-10 Three of the studs that held the propeller to the crankshaft flange were found with their fracture initiating on opposite sides of those studs. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-9 The propeller hub and engine crankshaft flange mating surfaces were found with areas of distress. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-1 The pilot of the incident airplane said that in-flight at 1800 feet above mean sea level, the engine seized, the propeller bolts sheared, the propeller fell to the ground, and that he landed the airplane without any damage to the airplane. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-11 A top overhaul was performed 85 tachometer hours prior to the accident. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-2 During an inspection of the engine, a 'B' nut on the oil pressure line to the turbocharger was found loose. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-4 The turbocharger and its housing were found with a dark, charred, oily substance on it. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-8 The number four cylinder head was found separated from its base. 
ntsb3621txt-1-5-5-0-6 The number one crankshaft journal was found blue. 
